04294nam a22005535i 9780773596498DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735964987 a10.1515/97807735964982doi  a(DE-B1597)656466  a(OCoLC)893309263  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN55b.R64 2014eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.93362231 aRogers, Janine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnified Fields :bScience and Literary Form /cJanine Rogers. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tFormal Strategies for Literature and Science -- tLiterary Form and Science -- tTurtles, Giants, Dwarves, and Pearls: The Poiesis of Science and Literature -- tPoetry -- tBeauty Bare: The Sonnet Form, Geometry, and Aesthetics -- tLife Forms: Elizabeth Bishop's “Sestina” and DNA Structure -- tThe Matter of Matter: The Atomic Sequences of Shane Rhodes and Edwin Morgan -- tProse -- tBeautiful Infestations: Margaret Atwood's Cat's Eye, Entomology, and the Superorganism -- tCrazy Love: Ronald Wright's A Scientific Romance in Time -- tThe Grandeur in This View of Life: Consciousness and Literary Form in Ian McEwan's Saturday -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiterary form presents an important opportunity for understanding the relationship between literature and science. Through a series of close readings of poetry and prose, Unified Fields demonstrates that formal structures in literature can relate to scientific concepts through their essential interpretive functions. Janine Rogers engages with a wide range of writing from Canadian, British, and American authors, including the poetry of Elizabeth Bishop and Robyn Sarah as well as prose by Margaret Atwood, Ian McEwan, and Stephen Hawking. She employs an interdisciplinary approach combining formalist, historical, and theoretical literary practice, informed by interpretive frameworks developed in the philosophy of science. Although dedicated to contemporary texts, Rogers's analysis is frequently rooted in historical contexts of form, including Euclidean geometry and medieval romance, developed when the distinction between literature and science was not so drastic. These historical connections demonstrate that continuities of form resonate in both contemporary literature and science. Through critical analysis and engaging prose, Unified Fields bridges an important disciplinary gap by revealing how literary practice informs scientific understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary form. 0aScience in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359649840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596498423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596498/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles